d during Berlin disorders:\n\nThere was virtually a complete stand-down of the Soviet 24th Air Army in East Germany, commencing 1300Z on 17 June, which was still continuing as of 1500Z on 19 June. During this period only two fighters and some transport aircraft were airborne; at the same time, there was unusually extensive ground-to-ground tuning on fighter and air warning circuits.\n\nThis inactivity is almost certainly related to the disorders in the Soviet sector of Berlin and other parts of East Germany.\n\nComment: These steps probably were part of general security measures pending determination of the extent of the uprisings. They may also have been due to Soviet concern over possible military action by the West", "token_count": 123, "token_end_0based": 124, "token_start_0based": 2, "token_text": "8 stand-down of soviet air activity noted during berlin disorders there was virtually a complete stand-down of the soviet 24th air army in east germany commencing 1300z on 17 june which was still continuing as of 1500z on 19 june during this period only two fighters and some transport aircraft were airborne at the same time there was unusually extensive ground-to-ground tuning on fighter and air warning circuits this inactivity is almost certainly related to the disorders in the soviet sector of berlin and other parts of east germany comment these steps probably were part of general security measures pending determination of the extent of the uprisings they may also have been due to soviet concern over possible military action by the west", "unred_source_page": 8}
